      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change <5% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh convergence study performed on pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. Stiffness QoI changed 1.8% between medium and fine mesh; GCI = 2.3%. Final mesh selected at medium refinement level. Discretization error within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals must converge to machine precision tolerances; iterative solver convergence criteria documented.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solver (SPARSE) employed for linear static analysis; iterative residual norm < 1e-8 achieved in all load steps. No convergence failures observed across all 11 model instances. Solver error contribution negligible."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup, boundary conditions, and load application by a second qualified analyst; documented checklist required.",
      "rationale": "Model setup independently reviewed by a second FEA analyst against a pre-defined checklist covering geometry import, material assignment, contact definitions, boundary conditions, and load application. All checklist items confirmed. No use errors identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification required that continuum linear elastic model with frictional contact is appropriate for titanium alloy pedicle screw construct under quasi-static loading below yield.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V alloy pedicle screw and rod modeled as isotropic linear elastic; UHMWPE vertebral body block modeled as linear elastic. Quasi-static loading to 40 mm displacement at 5 mm/min crosshead speed. Contact interfaces modeled with Coulomb friction (mu=0.3). Model form appropriate for pre-yield stiffness and yield force extraction. Literature precedent supports this model form for ASTM F1717 FEA."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions must be sourced from traceable measurements; input uncertainty ranges documented and propagated through UQ analysis.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (E=113.8 GPa, nu=0.342) and yield strength sourced from certified material test reports for the production lot. UHMWPE block modulus (E=0.88 GPa) from compressive testing per ASTM D695. Geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of representative screws and rods. Input uncertainty ranges for E, nu, and friction coefficient characterized via a screening sensitivity study embedded within the UQ workflow; results indicate E dominates stiffness QoI variability. Full uncertainty propagation performed via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000 runs) and reported in the UQ summary document."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Minimum N=5 experimental specimens per laboratory; specimens must be from production-equivalent lots with dimensional inspection records.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab A: N=6, Lab B: N=5). All specimens from production-equivalent manufacturing lots; dimensional inspection records confirm geometry within drawing tolerances. Sample size sufficient for statistical comparison per ASME V&V 40 guidance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or multiple load levels must be evaluated to characterize condition sensitivity.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 standard setup, 5 mm/min quasi-static, ambient temperature). Only one test condition evaluated; range of clinically relevant load angles and rates not explored. Achieved level (1) is below required level (2) for this factor. This gap is acknowledged and accepted given that F1717 is the regulatory standard configuration and the COU is limited to this specific test scenario."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs must be demonstrably equivalent to experimental specimen parameters; any discrepancies must be quantified and their effect on QoI bounded.",
      "rationale": "FEA model geometry constructed from CMM measurements of the same production-equivalent lot used for testing. Material properties assigned from certified test reports for the same material lot. Friction coefficient sensitivity bounded via UQ screening. Input parameter equivalency confirmed; no systematic discrepancies identified between model inputs and experimental specimen characterization."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (percent difference and E/uval) computed for each QoI; acceptance thresholds pre-specified before unblinding of experimental data.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs compared: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. Acceptance criteria pre-specified: percent difference <10% and E/uval <1.96. All three QoIs passed both criteria (stiffness: 4.1%, E/uval=1.41; yield force: 7.2%, E/uval=1.63; force at 40 mm: 5.8%, E/uval=1.22). Output comparison fully documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected must be directly relevant to the regulatory decision and must capture the mechanical performance attributes of concern for patient safety.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and align directly with FDA guidance for spinal implant mechanical testing. These quantities characterize the risk of construct failure leading to revision surgery. QoI relevance to COU confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity must replicate the physical scenario, loading conditions, and device configuration of the COU to a degree that supports extrapolation of credibility to the regulatory submission context.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, same ASTM F1717 test configuration, and same material lot as the regulatory submission. Two independent laboratories provide cross-laboratory reproducibility evidence. Validation activity is directly relevant to the COU; no extrapolation beyond tested configuration required."
    }
